<article>
    <h1>TASTES OF OUR TIME: COOK WITH CHRISTO&#xAD;PHER</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200731/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-31"><time>2020-07-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Food scholar and cook­book au­thor Christo­pher Tan (left) has a nice mini-se­ries of three videos cre­ated to high­light the Na­tional Mu­seum of Sin­ga­pore’s three his­tory gal­leries. Each episode is ded­i­cated to a par­tic­u­lar time pe­riod, and Tan demon­strates a recipe in­spired by the times.</p>
    <p>Episode One (str.sg/JeCV) fea­tures nankhatai, an In­dian short­bread bis­cuit. Episode Two (str.sg/JeCr) of­fers cit­rus bar­ley water, while Episode Three (str.sg/JeCK) dishes up sa­tay ayam goreng (above right). The first two recipes are sim­ple ones that novice cooks can try their hand at, while the sa­tay ayam goreng is a bit fid­dlier.</p>
    <p>The recipes are nice hooks to hang lit­tle snip­pets of his­tory on. For ex­am­ple, in Episode One, Tan talks about the cos­mopoli­tan in­flu­ences of the 1920s, which have lin­gered on in to­day’s lo­cal cuisines, in the form of con­fec­tions like nankhatai, rock buns and chicken pies. And Episode Three fea­tures clas­sic kitchen uten­sils such as a mor­tar and pes­tle and an iron wok and spat­ula, which are in the mu­seum’s col­lec­tion.</p>
    <p>WHERE: Na­tional Mu­seum of Sin­ga­pore’s YouTube chan­nel (str.sg/JeCj) AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>

